{{Infobox language family |name=Arutane–Sape |altname=Kalianan |region=[[Brazil–Venezuela border]] |familycolor=American |family = Proposed [[language family]] |child1=''[[Arutani language|Arutani]]'' |child2=''[[Sape language|Sape]]'' |child3=? ''[[Maku language of Roraima|Roraima Maku]]'' |glotto=none |map=Arutani-Sape.png |mapcaption=Documented location of Arutani–Sapé languages, the two most southern spots are Arutani villages, the northern one is Sapé location. }}
The '''Arutani–Sape''', also known as '''Awake–Kaliana''' or '''Kalianan''', are a proposed language family<ref name="Weinstein">{{cite book|last=Weinstein|first=Jay A. |title=Social and Cultural Change: Social Science for a Dynamic World|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date=2005-02-28|isbn=0-7425-2573-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wwDfXLLM-fsC&pg=PA94&dq=Arutani&as_brr=3&ei=gtuHSPebBIqeswPw0f3EDg&sig=ACfU3U1w9TUAusk8AQh3_VfYsOLhGYKDOw|page=94}}</ref> that includes two of the most poorly documented languages in South America, both of which are nearly extinct. They are at best only distantly related, but Kaufman (1990) finds the connection convincing. However, Migliazza & Campbell (1988) maintain that there is no evidence for linking them.<ref>Ernest Migliazza & Lyle Campbell, 1988. ''Panorama general de las lenguas indígenas en América''</ref> The two languages are,
*[[Arutani language|Arutani]]<ref name="Moseley-p177">{{cite book|last=Moseley|first=Christopher|title=Encyclopedia of the world's endangered languages|publisher=Routledge|date=2007-04-23|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dQt6XWloU10C&pg=PA177&dq=Arutani&as_brr=3&ei=gtuHSPebBIqeswPw0f3EDg&sig=ACfU3U1XNYJZA_N0ixmdg_RxtcSuVFu_0Q|page=177 | isbn=978-0-7007-1197-0}}</ref> (also known as Aoaqui, Auake, Auaque, Awake, Oewaku, Orotani, Uruak, Urutani) *[[Sape language|Sape]]<ref name="Moseley-p164">{{cite book|last=Moseley|first=Christopher|title=Encyclopedia of the world's endangered languages|publisher=Routledge|date=2007-04-23|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dQt6XWloU10C&pg=PA177&dq=Arutani&as_brr=3&ei=gtuHSPebBIqeswPw0f3EDg&sig=ACfU3U1XNYJZA_N0ixmdg_RxtcSuVFu_0Q#PPA164,M1|page=164 | isbn=978-0-7007-1197-0}}</ref> (also known as Caliana, Chirichano, Kaliana, Kariana)
Kaufman (1990) states that a further connection with [[Maku language of Roraima|Maku of Roraima]] is "promising".
==See also== *[[Macro-Puinavean]]
